    "Physics Constraints": "Conservation of mass (divergence of flux equals source), Darcy's law (flux = -K∇h), and boundary conditions (Dirichlet or Neumann) must be satisfied exactly or in a weak sense. High contrast and fine channels imply that the solution may have sharp gradients and localized features. Traditional numerical methods require fine meshes or multiscale techniques (e.g., MsFEM) to resolve channels. Physics-informed approaches can embed these constraints via residual losses, but boundary conditions must be enforced precisely.",
    "Model Choice": "For a single instance, a standard numerical solver (e.g., finite element with adaptive mesh refinement) is reliable and efficient; a physics-informed neural network (PINN) is an alternative if geometry is complex but may require careful training. For multiple realizations, a learned surrogate is justified: consider operator learning models like DeepONet or Fourier Neural Operator (FNO) that learn the mapping from permeability field K to head h. To incorporate physics, use a physics-informed operator (PINO) which includes PDE residual loss in the training. This avoids needing a large precomputed dataset. The high-contrast, fine-scale features suggest a multiscale architecture (e.g., multiscale DeepONet or hierarchical FNO) to capture both global and local effects. If limited data from full simulations, physics-informed training (without data) is preferred; otherwise, use a hybrid with sparse simulation data.",
