    "Problem Formalization": "We consider a domain Ω partitioned into subdomains Ω_i with constant permeability K_i. Between subdomains are sharp interfaces Γ_ij where K jumps by a factor of 100 (reference: K_low and K_high with ratio 100). Steady Darcy flow: ∇·(K∇h)=0 in each Ω_i (no sources). Boundary conditions are given but not specified; assume Dirichlet on part of ∂Ω and Neumann on the remainder. Head h is continuous across interfaces; normal flux K∇h·n is continuous. Consequently, the normal derivative of h jumps by a factor equal to the permeability ratio: (∇h·n)_low = 100 (∇h·n)_high if K_low is the smaller value. The geometry (e.g., 2D/3D) and exact BC values are missing; we assume a 2D domain for modeling, and BCs once available will be imposed as hard or soft constraints.",
    "Physics Constraints": "The residual is the strong form of the PDE within each subdomain: K_i ∇²h_i = 0. This differential form is valid because K_i is constant and h_i is smooth inside Ω_i. Across interfaces Γ_ij, we enforce two constraints: (i) head continuity: h_i = h_j, (ii) flux continuity: K_i ∇h_i·n_ij = K_j ∇h_j·n_ij, where n_ij is the unit normal from Ω_i to Ω_j. These interface conditions are incorporated as additional residual terms in the loss. The approach avoids differentiating the discontinuous K field and respects the physics where the strong form fails at interfaces.",
    "Model Choice": "We use separate fully-connected neural networks for each homogeneous subdomain. Each network φ_i(x; θ_i) outputs h_i in Ω_i. This representation naturally handles the piecewise-smooth solution: within each region the network approximates a smooth harmonic function, while across interfaces the discontinuity in the gradient (normal derivative jump factor 100) is captured via separate networks with shared interface constraints. A single network would struggle with the non-smoothness caused by the sharp permeability contrast. Separate networks also enable per-region gradient computation via automatic differentiation, avoiding mixed derivatives across material interfaces.",
    "Training Strategy": "Loss = λ_PDE Σ_i (1/N_i) Σ_{x∈Ω_i} (K_i ∇²φ_i)² + λ_BC * BC_loss + λ_iface_h * (1/N_iface) Σ_{x∈Γ} (φ_i - φ_j)² + λ_iface_flux * (1/N_iface) Σ_{x∈Γ} (K_i ∇φ_i·n - K_j ∇φ_j·n)². Collocation points are uniformly sampled in each Ω_i (50-100 per region) and on each interface Γ (50-100 points). Boundary points are sampled on ∂Ω. Weights λ are initially set to 1 and may be adaptively tuned to balance the losses; λ_iface_flux is given higher priority (e.g., 10) to enforce flux continuity. Optimizer: Adam for 10,000 iterations, then L-BFGS for 5,000 iterations. Additional points are concentrated near interfaces to improve constraint satisfaction.",
    "Validation Failure Risks": "Global L2 error can mask local violations of interface conditions. Specific risks: (i) head jump at interface (h_i ≠ h_j), (ii) flux imbalance (K_i ∇h_i·n ≠ K_j ∇h_j·n), (iii) incorrect ratio of normal derivatives (expected factor 100). Thus, validation must include interface-specific metrics: maximum absolute head difference at interface points, relative flux error (|K_i dh_i/dn - K_j dh_j/dn| / max(|K_i dh_i/dn|,|K_j dh_j/dn|)), and the ratio of normal derivatives across the interface (should be close to 100). These metrics should be monitored on a held-out set of interface points during training and reported in final evaluation. Failure to meet these interface constraints indicates the model has not properly learned the physics."
  }
